You are an independent skeptic verifying another agent's investigation of the RBK "Lode" subsystem (fetched-side artifact capture into GAR), in the repo at the current working directory. Do NOT trust their summary — RE-READ the cited files yourself.

Their area: scaffold (scaffold residue)

Their findings (JSON):
[
  {
    "claim": "Only the bole kind-letter constant exists. The reserved set (b/t/r/w/vw/vn) is documented in a comment but only RBGC_LODE_KIND_BOLE=\"b\" is defined; there is NO RBGC_LODE_KIND_TOOL/RELIQUARY/WSL/PODVM. The constant has exactly 2 consumers besides its definition: stamp minting and the divine legend.",
    "evidence": "Tools/rbk/rbgc_Constants.sh:217-219 (comment lists b/t/r/w/vw/vn, only `readonly RBGC_LODE_KIND_BOLE=\"b\"`); grep RBGC_LODE_KIND finds defn + rbldb_Bole.sh:197 (stamp) + rbldl_Lifecycle.sh:60 (legend) only",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "claim": "The GAR layout is a SINGLE flat root for all kinds — there is NO per-kind GAR-layout entry to add. The kind-letter is encoded only in the touchmark string (`<kind-letter><stamp>`), and every Lode lives directly under RBGL_LODES_ROOT regardless of kind. So 'GAR-layout entry' is NOT part of the scaffold residue for any kind.",
    "evidence": "Tools/rbk/rbgl_GarLayout.sh:30,52 (single `RBGL_LODES_ROOT=\"${RBGC_GAR_CATEGORY_LODES}\"`, shape `${RBGL_LODES_ROOT}/<kind-letter><stamp>:<member-tag>`); RBS0-SpecTop.adoc:2116-2118 (one namespace, members ride as tags, never path-segment siblings)",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "claim": "Three capture colophons are MISSING from the zipper: rbw-lF (fetter/tool), rbw-lC (conclave/reliquary), rbw-lU (underpin/wsl), rbw-lI (immure/podvm) — none are enrolled. Only ensconce (rbw-lE), divine (rbw-ld), banish (rbw-lB) exist in the RBZ__GROUP_LODE block.",
    "evidence": "Tools/rbk/rbz_zipper.sh:86-90 (group + 3 buz_enroll lines only); `grep fetter|conclave|underpin|immure` across Tools/rbk and tt/ returns nothing in code (only the acronym map)",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "claim": "Three theurge colophon-consts are MISSING in rbtdgc_consts.rs: only RBTDGC_ENSCONCE_BOLE/DIVINE_LODES/BANISH_LODE exist (rbw-lE/ld/lB). No fetter/conclave/underpin/immure const.",
    "evidence": "Tools/rbk/rbtd/src/rbtdgc_consts.rs:34-36 (three consts only)",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "claim": "The theurge manifest has ONE shared kind-agnostic fixture (lode-lifecycle) requiring the three existing colophons — there are no per-kind fixtures. Whether new verticals add manifest entries is a TEST-coverage choice, not a registration prerequisite for slating; the existing fixture exercises the spine path generically.",
    "evidence": "Tools/rbk/rbtd/src/rbtdrm_manifest.rs:54-56 (single `RBTDRM_FIXTURE_LODE_LIFECYCLE`), :161-165 (required colophons = ENSCONCE_BOLE/DIVINE_LODES/BANISH_LODE)",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "claim": "The divine-legend is the ONE genuinely kind-coupled registration point besides the kind-letter constant. It prints 'one entry per implemented kind' and currently has a single hardcoded bole row; each new kind must add a row. This is the shared read-side surface that every vertical touches.",
    "evidence": "Tools/rbk/rbldl_Lifecycle.sh:54-60 (comment 'One entry per implemented kind' + single `printf ... RBGC_LODE_KIND_BOLE ... \"bole\"`)",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "claim": "divine/banish (and the spec'd-but-unimplemented augur) are explicitly kind-AGNOSTIC — the kind is decoded from the touchmark's leading letter. So the remaining verticals do NOT each need their own divine/banish; the per-kind work is the capture verb (ensconce-analogue) plus the legend row + kind-letter constant.",
    "evidence": "RBS0-SpecTop.adoc:1464 ('Read-only and kind-agnostic — the kind is decoded from the touchmark's leading letter'), :1474 (augur 'Read-only and kind-agnostic')",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "claim": "Each kind body file (the rblds_ spine consumer) is the per-vertical work, NOT scaffold residue. The bole body rbldb_Bole.sh mints the stamp from RBGC_LODE_KIND_BOLE (line 197) and rides zrbld_spine_dispatch; reserved module letters RBLDT/RBLDR/RBLDW/RBLDV are legend-only with no files. New bodies are the verticals themselves.",
    "evidence": "Tools/rbk/rbldb_Bole.sh:197 (`z_stamp=\"${RBGC_LODE_KIND_BOLE}...\"`), :93-96 (rides spine); claude-rbk-acronyms.md:49 ('Reserved (legend only, no files this heat ...): RBLDT tool, RBLDR reliquary, RBLDW wsl, RBLDV podvm')",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "claim": "augur (rbw-la, rbld_augur) is SPEC'd (RBSLA-lode_augur.adoc exists, quoin rbtgo_lode_augur in RBS0) but ABSENT from all code/registries. Today the single-Lode inspect lives inside rbld_divine, reached via rbw-ld with a touchmark folio. augur is a kind-agnostic read verb, adjacent to but distinct from the kind-registration residue.",
    "evidence": "RBS0-SpecTop.adoc:1468-1476 + RBSLA-lode_augur.adoc exist; grep for rbld_augur/rbw-la/augur across rbz_zipper.sh, rbld0_cli.sh, rbldl_Lifecycle.sh, rbtdgc_consts.rs returns 'AUGUR ABSENT FROM ALL CODE/REGISTRIES'; rbldl_Lifecycle.sh:118-151 (inspect-one-Lode lives in rbld_divine)",
    "confidence": "high"
  },
  {
    "claim": "podvm is two kind-letters (vw podvm-wsl, vn podvm-native) — the only two-letter codes — so a podvm vertical implies TWO kind-letter constants and TWO legend rows, not one. This is the one place the per-kind residue is not 1:1 with the 4 kinds.",
    "evidence": "Tools/rbk/rbgc_Constants.sh:218 ('vw podvm-wsl | vn podvm-native'); RBS0-SpecTop.adoc:2160-2161 ('one- or two-letter kind code ... vw podvm-wsl, vn podvm-native')",
    "confidence": "high"
  }
]

Their recommendation_input:
SCAFFOLD-RESIDUE INVENTORY (the kind-registration surface ₣BX did NOT build that must land before the 4 verticals can be slated):

The residue is SMALLER than the prompt's six-artifact-per-kind checklist suggests, because three of the six are non-existent-as-separate-things:
- GAR-layout entry: NOT a thing. The rbi_ld namespace is a single flat root (rbgl_GarLayout.sh:52); the kind lives only in the touchmark string. Zero per-kind layout work.
- divine/banish colophons: NOT per-kind. They are kind-agnostic (RBS0:1464), decoding kind from the touchmark letter. No new divine/banish per vertical.
- theurge manifest entry: a test-coverage choice (one shared lode-lifecycle fixture exists), not a slating prerequisite.

The GENUINE residue — the shared registration points each future vertical depends on — is THREE coupled edits, all in already-existing files:
1. Kind-letter constant(s) in rbgc_Constants.sh (RBGC_LODE_KIND_TOOL=\"t\", _RELIQUARY=\"r\", _WSL=\"w\", and podvm needs TWO: _PODVM_WSL=\"vw\" + _PODVM_NATIVE=\"vn\"). 5 constants for 4 kinds.
2. Divine-legend rows in rbldl_Lifecycle.sh:54-60 (one printf row per implemented kind; podvm = two rows).
3. (Arguably) reserving the capture colophons rbw-lF/lC/lU/lI + their RBZ_ zipper consts + RBTDGC_ theurge consts — but these are naturally authored WITH each vertical's body (the colophon points at the verb that does not yet exist), so they are vertical-local, not scaffold.

JUDGMENT — ONE serial pace vs split: This is genuinely ONE small serial pace, and it should land first. Its true content is narrow: (a) promote the kind-letter comment block in rbgc_Constants.sh into the full set of constants (b/t/r/w/vw/vn — bole already done), and (b) leave the divine legend as-is (it grows per-vertical, since a legend row for an unimplemented kind would lie). That is essentially a single-file constant-promotion. It does NOT want splitting — it is a handful of `readonly` lines in one file plus possibly the augur landing (see below). Splitting four trivial constant additions into four paces would be over-segmentation.

ONE CAVEAT for the planner: augur (rbw-la) is spec'd (RBSLA exists, quoin in RBS0) but unimplemented — today single-Lode inspect is folded into rbld_divine. augur is kind-agnostic read infrastructure, NOT kind-registration residue, so it does NOT block the verticals and should NOT be bundled into the scaffold-residue pace. It is a separate landable verb. If the planner wants the read surface complete before verticals, augur is a distinct sibling pace, not part of this one.

PODVM ASYMMETRY: flag that podvm is the only kind needing two kind-letters/two legend rows (vw/vn) and is described as multi-member with two quay families — when that vertical is slated it carries roughly double the per-kind registration of the others. That does not affect the scaffold-residue pace (which just defines all constants up front) but matters for sizing the podvm vertical itself.

Independently check the LOAD-BEARING factual claims against the actual files. For each, return whether it holds (with a note citing what you found). Then — most important — state in `corrections` anything they got WRONG, any citation that's off, or anything they MISSED that would change the recommendation. If the recommendation stands as-is, set corrections to an empty string.

